metadata.name: YYYSEED #490
metadata.description:
🔥 BURN NOTICE: This is a FIVE DAY "open edition" to celebrate the launch of fx(params). The project is open for minting from the start of Monday until midnight Friday (GMT).

YYYSEED is an artwork with an aesthetic that works across digital, print and pen plotting mediums, leaning towards the minimalistic nature of drawing machines. SVGs can be exported for this purpose.

I've designed the algorithm to work best for this with the default settings, you should be good to go right out of the box. You can explore the design space a little further using the parameters (more details below).

If you're planning on plotting the work at larger sizes (A2, A1), then the "Override suggest lines" is there for you to cram more of them into the extra space.

PARAMS ::::::::::::::

The initial settings of the parameters are what I think best for the look I'm trying to achieve as the artist: minimal pen plotting work. This comes from the "Suggested" and "Random for hash" values.

You can take the design away from that by turning the "Use suggested lines" and "Use suggested destroyer" options off, and using your own values with the slider.

"Random for hash" means the feature has been randomly selected and fixed for the current hash and won't change. For example, if the hash is 'ooABCD' and the grid's "Random for hash" picks 3x4, then it will always be 3x4 for that hash, it isn't random each time you change sometime. Picking a new hash however will then randomly pick a new (fixed) option.

DANGER SEED :::::::::

USE OF THE DANGER SEED IS NOT RECOMMENDED. If you set the DANGER SEED, the value will be encoded along with the rest of the params (where it can be decoded) in the stored data of the mint, along with the token.

The DANGER SEED will only take effect if it starts with 'YYY', it will STOMP all over the other settings, including the hash.

INSTRUCTIONS ::::::::

h - Toggle highres mode on/off (starts off)
t - Toggle paper background on/off
s - Save png (in highres if toggled on)
1-6 - Save SVGs for plotting A1, A2, A3, A4, A5, A6

PEN PLOTTING ::::::::

Press 1-6 to select which A1-6 size paper you want to plot onto, the the system will download one or more files for you to use, one file per colour.

Please tag #plottertwitter, or #penplotter on twitter, instagram & mastodon

PRINTING ::::::::::::

The output of the high resolution version is 6,144 x 8,192 pixels. That will print at the following sizes.

300dpi: 20.48 x 27.31 inches (52.02 x 69.35 cm)
200dpi: 30.72 x 40.96 inches (78.03 x 104.03 cm)

300dpi is recommended, but 200dpi should be fine for this design. I suggest turning the paper texture off if you're printing onto textured archival paper, you can leave it on when printing onto smooth white paper.

metadata.name: Rangxel #406
Rangxel #310
Rangxel #278
Perpetual Oscillations  #37
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Fuzzy Logic #4
metadata.description:
In the middle of chaos emerges order,
Invisible but present, waiting to be captured,
Waiting for the limits to be placed,
A matter of scale and boundary conditions
Waiting to form and deform 
Into one another 

Change, is that all there is to life?

This piece combines random noise of multiple types with basic geometric shapes to create abstract urban representations of unknown spaces!

Press 's' to save and 'd' to destroy! 

Jaalibandar 2022

metadata.name: Wild Palms #164
metadata.description:
When I was a child walking with my father in the park, he once told me if I could hear the trees talking to each other. I listened, and in the noise of the leaves and seeds in the wind, I truly recognized their languages and voices. I was so overwhelmed by the depth and diversity of the world and the creatures that inhabit it, that it is still one of my most vivid memories. 

When I walk through parks or forests, I always listen to what they say. It is unlikely that I will ever be able to engage in their dialogue, but it is always like a touch of the magical immensity of life.

Wild Palms is the name of a gallery of our friends with whom it is always a pleasure to talk in the language of humans, and they have a garden right in the gallery.
In the project we mix childhood memories and friendship, the aesthetics of woodcuts, Polaroid and hand-printed photos with echoes of the digital voice of our present.

Thanks to YulikolaY for getting the code ready for production.

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

January, 2023

metadata.name: The Valley #71
metadata.description:
"The Valley" is a unique collection of generative art that explores the mysterious and enigmatic valleys on distant planets. Using algorithms, each piece captures the beauty and mood of the different valleys, some of which are more friendly and inviting, while others are bleak and ominous. The unpredictable and abstract nature of the art invites the viewer to see the beauty in the unknown and to be fascinated by the infinite possibilities of the universe. The glitches and digital distortions add an element of unpredictability, enhancing the sense of mystery and intrigue and inviting the viewer to be fully immersed in the art.

The art is inspired by the aesthetic of old sci-fi magazine covers, with a modern twist that pushes the boundaries of contemporary art. Each piece is a visual representation of the imagination and a tribute to the beauty and fascination of the unknown. Through this collection, the viewer is invited to experience the unknown in a captivating and thought-provoking way. The art invites the viewer to ponder the mysteries of the universe and to be inspired by the beauty of the unknown. This collection is a celebration of the imagination and a testament to the power of generative art to explore the unknown and bring it to life.

Genuary 2023: Landscapes

metadata.name: Messy Garden #15
metadata.description:
Messy Garden is a response to the ongoing global crises from climate change to the war, not to mention economic downfall amidst other catastrophic events. However, that seems insignificant to the accelerating infrastructural systems covering our planet inch by inch with every passing year. Growth and scale, two buzzwords of the modern economic machinery, driven by a yearning for a utopic society, although we move closer to a dystopic one. 

This piece, started from a single petal, which is a certain section of the parametric surface, pillow, instanced over and over to create a single flower, instanced over and over to create multiple flowers, along with the help of l systems to create the base and the entire composition fed to a deformer to create distortion. A reminder that there are more things to life than being mere rats in the assembly line producing elements to develop the accidental megastructure.

-----------

Press 'S' in Live view to save PNG
*Might take a while to load, please be patient! Heavy duty system recommended for viewing.

Made with cables.gl
@jaalibandar 2023

metadata.name: Aftershock #76
metadata.description:
Turkey was hit by two devastating earthquakes at 6/02/2023 effecting multiple cities.

Aftershock is created to help and support people in earthquake region. 100% of the revenue from primary sales will be send to non governmental organization AHBAP after it's converted to ethereum. All donation will sent from atimtay.eth and will be shared publicly from my twitter account


Artwork info:

Aftershock is based on "Metropolix IX' algorithm. In Metropolis the parameter space was constrained and the cells were painted in a fashion which would create city silhouettes. In Aftershock i removed the constraints and changed the all rulesets and palettes which would give us chaos maybe you can call it a collapsed city.


Features:

6 color palettes and 1 monochrome 
3 subdivison levels 2,3,4 
2 aspect ratios 
10 divison styles 
and some other hidden randomized parameters which doesn't appear on the features but effecting overall outcome

Press 1 to 8 to export PNG at increasing resolution

Murat Atimtay 2023 www.atimtay.xyz

metadata.name: WISH* #9
metadata.description:
WISH*

> What do you wish for? < 

WISH continues exploring the *poofs* from my previous project "slow draw (rare version)", this time placing the inscription beneath the poofs. 

Arcs, circles, triangles, and beziers inscribe with variations on spacing and rotation in carefully chosen color palettes to invoke memory and emotion. 

From 55 background color palettes, 25 poof color palettes and 4 filter layers comes an endless array of playful poof wishscapes. 

Sometimes an egg is revealed to signal Spring's entrance into 2023.

This project began in the December depths of winter and has delivered me joyfully into Spring. 

May it find you well and may it bring you what you wish for.

In gratitude, 

cari ann shim sham*

metadata.name: Glossolalia #237
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.
